<h2>HVAC Systems for St Louis</h2>
<p>St. Louis's Cold-Mixed climate zone requires HVAC systems capable of handling both summer temperatures reaching the 90s with high humidity and winter lows often dropping below freezing. For this climate, high-efficiency heat pumps with SEER ratings of 16-20 and HSPF ratings of 9-10 are ideal, providing both heating and cooling efficiently. Gas furnaces paired with central air conditioning units are also popular, with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher recommended for the heating component and SEER ratings of at least 16 for cooling.</p>

<p>Given St. Louis's humidity levels, proper dehumidification capabilities are essential, making variable-speed systems particularly valuable. These systems can run longer at lower speeds, providing better humidity control while maintaining consistent temperatures. For the 1,720 square foot average home size in St. Louis, a 2.5 to 3-ton system typically provides adequate capacity, though proper load calculations should always be performed to account for insulation levels, window efficiency, and home orientation.</p>

